## 5. WHEN TO SEEK PROFESSIONAL HELP

**YOU SHOULD SEEK PROFESSIONAL MEDICAL OR MENTAL HEALTH CARE IF:**

**Regarding Panic Attacks:**
- Panic attacks occur frequently (more than once per week)
- Panic attacks are getting worse or more intense
- Panic attacks last longer than 30 minutes
- You avoid places or situations due to fear of panic attacks
- Panic attacks interfere with work, school, or relationships
- You develop new physical symptoms during panic attacks
- Panic attacks occur with chest pain or breathing difficulties
- You're unsure if symptoms are panic attacks or something else

**Regarding Mental Health:**
- You experience depression, hopelessness, or persistent sadness
- You have thoughts of death, dying, or suicide
- You experience anxiety that disrupts daily functioning
- You develop new or worsening mental health symptoms
- You use alcohol or drugs to cope with panic or anxiety
- You experience trauma or PTSD symptoms
- Your quality of life is significantly impaired

**Regarding Physical Health:**
- You have a history of heart problems
- You have respiratory conditions (asthma, COPD)
- You experience new or unexplained physical symptoms
- Your symptoms don't match typical panic attack patterns
- You're pregnant and experiencing panic attacks
- You have other chronic medical conditions

**Remember:**
- Self-help tools are not a substitute for professional care
- Many people benefit from BOTH therapy AND self-help tools
- There is no shame in seeking help
- Professional treatment for panic disorder is highly effective

